1
00:00:00,033 --> 00:00:01,233
hello everyone

2
00:00:01,266 --> 00:00:04,533
today we are going to have a quick look at Steve's Factory Manager

3
00:00:04,533 --> 00:00:07,033
this is a very powerful and useful mod

4
00:00:07,033 --> 00:00:10,600
which can help you solve all sorts of logistic puzzles

5
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,600
but let's start by looking at it block by block

6
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,900
the main block of this mod is the Machine Inventory Manager

7
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:19,233
this will be the controller of our setups

8
00:00:19,233 --> 00:00:22,200
that will run whatever code we will instruct it with

9
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:25,800
the other important block we will be using is the inventory cable

10
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:30,600
which will allow the machine inventory manager to interact with whatever the cable touches

11
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:32,466
other than those two blocks

12
00:00:32,466 --> 00:00:35,500
there are about a dozen more added by this mod

13
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:38,000
but we will see those later on when needed

14
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,633
and now after throwing together a bunch of machines

15
00:00:41,633 --> 00:00:44,233
let's see what we can do using SFM

16
00:00:44,266 --> 00:00:47,866
to get started we are going to create our first command

17
00:00:47,866 --> 00:00:48,600
a trigger

18
00:00:48,600 --> 00:00:51,466
by clicking on the first of the buttons on the left

19
00:00:51,466 --> 00:00:54,233
this created a new block for our program

20
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:56,600
like any other that we will be creating

21
00:00:56,600 --> 00:01:01,100
we can move it around by dragging it from that little square in the top corner

22
00:01:01,166 --> 00:01:03,566
and to make things more understandable

23
00:01:03,566 --> 00:01:10,833
we can also rename our blocks however we like by clicking on the save as icon after opening the block with a left click

24
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:16,366
this trigger command will be the start of the instruction that our manager will be doing

25
00:01:16,566 --> 00:01:20,566
we can set how often we want that to happen in the interval section

26
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:24,700
next, we have to connect the commands with the instructions for the manager

27
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,600
the two simplest ones are input and output commands

28
00:01:28,600 --> 00:01:34,566
those two instructions specify from where and which items can be taken and placed by the manager

29
00:01:34,566 --> 00:01:38,666
in the inventory tab, we can select from where the items can be moved

30
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:40,433
but as you can see

31
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:43,833
it's not always easy to figure out which chest is which

32
00:01:43,833 --> 00:01:47,000
to avoid confusion, we can make a factory labeler

33
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,400
which will allow us to name inventories

34
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:53,266
making it easy to spot which one is the chest we want to use

35
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:55,666
we rename each one of those chests

36
00:01:55,666 --> 00:02:00,800
and then we proceed into selecting a chest to use as input and one to use as output

37
00:02:01,666 --> 00:02:05,100
after selecting an input inventory and an output inventory

38
00:02:05,166 --> 00:02:08,800
we have to connect the block the way we want the program to flow

39
00:02:08,833 --> 00:02:10,433
starting from the start

40
00:02:10,433 --> 00:02:13,866
we take from the A chest and then we drop in the B chest

41
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:21,633
we can verify the program works by placing some stuff in the chest labeled A and retrieving it in the chest labeled B

42
00:02:21,966 --> 00:02:25,866
however, those two commands have other options we can add

43
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:32,366
for example, using the items tab, we can filter which items we want to be moved

44
00:02:33,033 --> 00:02:35,366
that is some very basic filtering

45
00:02:35,366 --> 00:02:38,066
but there is more advanced things we can do

46
00:02:38,233 --> 00:02:40,300
if we right click the filtered item

47
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:42,166
we can set other options

48
00:02:42,166 --> 00:02:44,900
such as how many items should be moved

49
00:02:45,033 --> 00:02:47,100
and one cool feature is that

50
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:49,600
if we specify an amount as blacklisted

51
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:52,500
we can keep that amount inside the input inventory

52
00:02:52,833 --> 00:02:54,900
if we select two inputs

53
00:02:54,900 --> 00:02:57,966
the amount to keep will be across both of the chests

54
00:02:57,966 --> 00:03:01,100
meaning only one of the two will keep that amount

55
00:03:01,300 --> 00:03:05,600
we can change that behavior by changing the multi selection settings

56
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:08,266
if we run the command once per target

57
00:03:08,266 --> 00:03:12,766
we will be able to keep a fixed amount of items in each of the selected inventories

58
00:03:12,900 --> 00:03:17,266
that is something which can be very useful in some automation setups

59
00:03:17,366 --> 00:03:20,266
the next instruction we can use is the condition

60
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:22,700
as we notice right after adding it

61
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:24,833
this one has an extra circle

62
00:03:25,033 --> 00:03:30,200
the condition will check inside the specified inventories for the presence of a specified item

63
00:03:30,366 --> 00:03:32,433
depending on the finding result

64
00:03:32,433 --> 00:03:36,433
it will chose one of two possible consecutive instructions

65
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:42,366
for example, here we can set to follow the old instruction if some cobblestone is present

66
00:03:42,466 --> 00:03:46,633
otherwise, if not cobblestone is present in the chest named A

67
00:03:46,633 --> 00:03:49,100
the program will take a different path

68
00:03:50,466 --> 00:03:53,100
to make the condition check for any item

69
00:03:53,166 --> 00:03:56,000
we can change the detection to match any block

70
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,500
next we have flow blocks

71
00:03:59,666 --> 00:04:04,233
those allow merging or splitting of the program execution flows

72
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:11,166
liquid input, output and condition are the fluid version of the previously seen blocks

73
00:04:11,666 --> 00:04:14,200
and there is also an energy variant

74
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:18,600
next, there are Redstone emitters and Redstone conditions

75
00:04:19,633 --> 00:04:23,233
those two instructions will work with two new kind of blocks

76
00:04:23,233 --> 00:04:25,233
Redstone emitter and receiver

77
00:04:25,233 --> 00:04:29,233
and will allow for interacting with external Redstone signals

78
00:04:29,866 --> 00:04:32,400
and using the various option tabs

79
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:36,566
we can achieve pretty much any kind of Redstone behavior we want

80
00:04:37,366 --> 00:04:39,466
next we have command groups

81
00:04:39,833 --> 00:04:44,866
those instruction blocks will act as a container for many more instruction blocks

82
00:04:45,233 --> 00:04:49,500
we can get in and out of those with the opposite navigation controls

83
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:53,800
and here we can make a chain of commands act as a single command

84
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:56,100
saving space in the main program

85
00:04:56,466 --> 00:04:59,733
if we want this group to interact with the main program flow

86
00:04:59,733 --> 00:05:03,033
we can add some command group nodes to do so

87
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:06,966
making groups of commands has one extra special feature

88
00:05:06,966 --> 00:05:11,633
if we are doing some complex setups with a list of slightly different commands

89
00:05:11,633 --> 00:05:14,100
we can make a group and then duplicate it

90
00:05:14,500 --> 00:05:19,500
finally the last interesting thing I want to show is the camouflage upgrade

91
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:24,033
this one works with camouflage cables and transforming cables

92
00:05:24,033 --> 00:05:27,400
which we better add to a cable cluster for proper cabling

93
00:05:27,666 --> 00:05:31,800
with that we can change the texture of the cables for better looks

94
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:33,133
but more importantly

95
00:05:33,133 --> 00:05:39,833
we can change the cable size to allow interacting with blocks that could otherwise be hidden by the cables

96
00:05:39,966 --> 00:05:43,000
and now let's see some examples of usage

97
00:05:43,166 --> 00:05:44,433
in this water plant

98
00:05:44,433 --> 00:05:52,100
we are using SFM to keep exactly 25 liters of hydrochloric acid in the input hatch when the Redstone signal is on

99
00:05:52,233 --> 00:05:56,100
to do so, we check every second the Redstone condition

100
00:05:56,233 --> 00:06:01,300
if there is red stone, then we check if there is already fluid inside the hatch

101
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:03,200
if so, we do nothing

102
00:06:03,266 --> 00:06:07,200
otherwise, if there is red stone and no fluid inside the hatch

103
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:11,766
we take from the main tank 25 liters of acid and move it to the hatch

104
00:06:11,833 --> 00:06:14,766
that could have probably been achieved by other means

105
00:06:14,766 --> 00:06:19,433
but it's a good simple example to show what SFM can do and how to use it

106
00:06:20,033 --> 00:06:25,066
one other cool trick we are doing with SFM is on the next water purification plant

107
00:06:25,066 --> 00:06:31,166
where we move an arbitrary item between inventories to keep track of which operation we did last time

108
00:06:31,466 --> 00:06:36,300
as next example, we can automate bacterial vats using SFM

109
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:40,266
the main objective here is keeping the output hatches half filled

110
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:44,400
but we also prevent wasting radioactive input materials

111
00:06:44,900 --> 00:06:50,666
to do so we extract everything but 31 buckets of fluid from the output hatches

112
00:06:50,833 --> 00:06:59,833
then we check that we have enough ingredients ready and enough output space available before inserting the radioactive rods to start the process

113
00:07:00,066 --> 00:07:02,666
next we have more complex tasks

114
00:07:02,666 --> 00:07:05,600
such as automating thaumcraft infusion

115
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:08,400
the program has two parts

116
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:12,600
which part is run depends on the presence of an item in the middle of the altar

117
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:15,500
if there is no item in the altar

118
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:19,833
then we check if we have a crafting order ready in the input chest

119
00:07:19,900 --> 00:07:21,900
if the whole thing has nothing to do

120
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:25,100
we shut off the world accelerators to save energy

121
00:07:25,433 --> 00:07:27,966
but if we have something ready to be crafted

122
00:07:27,966 --> 00:07:30,233
we move every item on the pedestal

123
00:07:30,466 --> 00:07:36,466
to do so, we have a group with all the insertion commands that will fill the pedestal in a proper order

124
00:07:36,666 --> 00:07:41,366
starting with the first item that is the one supposed to go in the middle of the altar

125
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:44,433
next we start all the World Accelerators

126
00:07:44,433 --> 00:07:47,766
and pulse the infusion claw to start the process

127
00:07:48,066 --> 00:07:49,966
on the next run of the program

128
00:07:49,966 --> 00:07:52,633
we expect an item to be in the middle of the altar

129
00:07:52,866 --> 00:07:55,300
but to make sure the process is complete

130
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:59,466
we also make sure there are no other items waiting for the process

131
00:07:59,833 --> 00:08:04,833
if so we wait one extra half second to make sure everything stabilized

132
00:08:04,833 --> 00:08:07,866
then we proceed into retrieving the finished item

133
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:11,000
and we also shut off the World Accelerators

134
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:13,500
if you want to see more examples

135
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:16,200
you can check my GTNH season 2

136
00:08:16,433 --> 00:08:17,400
bye bye

137
00:00:00,033 --> 00:00:01,233
大家好

138
00:00:01,266 --> 00:00:04,533
今天我们来看看SFM

139
00:00:04,533 --> 00:00:07,033
这是一个非常强大和有用的mod

140
00:00:07,033 --> 00:00:10,600
可以帮助你解决各种物流难题

141
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,600

但是让我们一个方块一个方块来


142
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,900
此mod的主要方块是工厂管理器

143
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:19,233
这将是产线物流的控制器

144
00:00:19,233 --> 00:00:22,200
它将运行我们给他写的代码

145
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:25,800
我们将使用的另一个重要方块是工厂线缆

146
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:30,600
这将允许工厂管理器与线缆接触的任何东西进行交互

147
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:32,466
除了那两个方块

148
00:00:32,466 --> 00:00:35,500

这个mod还添加了十几个方块


149
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:38,000
但我们稍后会在需要时介绍它们

150
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,633
现在在组装了一堆机器之后

151
00:00:41,633 --> 00:00:44,233
让我们看看SFM可以做些什么

152
00:00:44,266 --> 00:00:47,866
首先，我们将创建我们的第一个指令

153
00:00:47,866 --> 00:00:48,600
触发器

154
00:00:48,600 --> 00:00:51,466
通过单击左侧的第一个按钮

155
00:00:51,466 --> 00:00:54,233
这为我们的程序创建了一个新的模块

156
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:56,600
就像我们将创建的任何其他模块一样

157
00:00:56,600 --> 00:01:01,100
我们可以通过拖动左上角的小方块来移动它

158
00:01:01,166 --> 00:01:03,566
为了让事情更容易理解

159
00:01:03,566 --> 00:01:10,833

我们也可以在左键单击打开模块
更改名称，并单击另存为图标重命名模块


160
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:16,366
这个触发指令将是处理器将要执行的指令的开始

161
00:01:16,566 --> 00:01:20,566
我们可以在间隔部分设置处理器工作的时间间隔

162
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:24,700
接下来，我们必须连接给管理器的指令

163
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,600
最简单的两个指令是输入和输出

164
00:01:28,600 --> 00:01:34,566
这两个指令指定了管理器
可以从哪里取走或者放置哪些物品

165
00:01:34,566 --> 00:01:38,666

在库存选项卡中，我们可以选择可以从哪取出物品


166
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:40,433
但如你所见

167
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:43,833
弄清楚哪个箱子是哪个并不总是容易的

168
00:01:43,833 --> 00:01:47,000
为避免混淆，我们可以制作工厂贴标器

169
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,400
这将使我们能够命名库存

170
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:53,266
让我们更容易发现哪个是我们想要使用的箱子

171
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:55,666
我们给每个箱子重新命名

172
00:01:55,666 --> 00:02:00,800
然后我们继续选择一个箱子作为输入，一个作为输出

173
00:02:01,666 --> 00:02:05,100
选择输入库存和输出库存后

174
00:02:05,166 --> 00:02:08,800
我们必须按照我们希望程序执行的顺序连接模块

175
00:02:08,833 --> 00:02:10,433
从触发器开始

176
00:02:10,433 --> 00:02:13,866
我们从A类箱子中取出，然后放入B类箱子中

177
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:21,633
我们可以通过"在标为A的箱子里放一些东西
并在标为B的箱子里取回它"来验证程序有正常工作

178
00:02:21,966 --> 00:02:25,866
但是，这两个指令还有其他可选项

179
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:32,366
例如，使用物品选项卡，我们可以过滤要移动的物品

180
00:02:33,033 --> 00:02:35,366
这是一些非常基本的过滤

181
00:02:35,366 --> 00:02:38,066
但我们可以做更高级的事情

182
00:02:38,233 --> 00:02:40,300
如果我们右键单击过滤后的物品

183
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:42,166
我们可以设置其他选项

184
00:02:42,166 --> 00:02:44,900
例如应该移动多少物品

185
00:02:45,033 --> 00:02:47,100
一个很酷的功能是

186
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:49,600
如果我们给黑名单物品指定数量

187
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:52,500
我们可以将该数量的物品保留在输入库存中

188
00:02:52,833 --> 00:02:54,900
如果我们选择两个输入

189
00:02:54,900 --> 00:02:57,966

要保留的数量将作用于两个箱子的整体


190
00:02:57,966 --> 00:03:01,100
这意味着两个箱子中只有一个会保留这个数量的物品

191
00:03:01,300 --> 00:03:05,600
我们可以通过更改多选设置来改变这种行为

192
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:08,266
如果我们给每个目标都运行一次指令

193
00:03:08,266 --> 00:03:12,766
我们将能够在每个选定的库存中保留固定数量的物品

194
00:03:12,900 --> 00:03:17,266
这在某些自动化设置中非常有用

195
00:03:17,366 --> 00:03:20,266
我们可以使用的下一个指令是条件模块

196
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:22,700
正如我们在添加后立即注意到的那样

197
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:24,833
这个多了一个圆圈

198
00:03:25,033 --> 00:03:30,200
条件模块将检查指定库存中是否存在指定物品

199
00:03:30,366 --> 00:03:32,433
取决于库存返回的结果

200
00:03:32,433 --> 00:03:36,433
它将从两个可能的连续指令中选择一个

201
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:42,366
例如，如果存在一些圆石
我们可以在这里设置为遵循旧指令

202
00:03:42,466 --> 00:03:46,633
否则，如果在A的箱子中没有圆石存在

203
00:03:46,633 --> 00:03:49,100
程序将走上不同的道路

204
00:03:50,466 --> 00:03:53,100
要检查库存中是否存在物品，无论种类

205
00:03:53,166 --> 00:03:56,000
我们可以更改检测以匹配任何方块

206
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,500
接下来是流程模块

207
00:03:59,666 --> 00:04:04,233
这些允许合并或拆分程序执行流

208
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:11,166
液体输入、输出和条件模块是先前看到的模块的流体版本

209
00:04:11,666 --> 00:04:14,200

还有类似的能量模块


210
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:18,600
接下来是红石发射器和红石条件模块

211
00:04:19,633 --> 00:04:23,233

这两个指令将和两种新方块搭配工作


212
00:04:23,233 --> 00:04:25,233
红石发射器和接收器

213
00:04:25,233 --> 00:04:29,233
并允许与外部红石信号交互

214
00:04:29,866 --> 00:04:32,400
通过使用各种选项卡

215
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:36,566
我们几乎可以实现任何我们想要的红石行为

216
00:04:37,366 --> 00:04:39,466
接下来我们有指令组

217
00:04:39,833 --> 00:04:44,866
指令组将充当更多指令模块的容器

218
00:04:45,233 --> 00:04:49,500

我们可以通过点击边栏的左箭头进出指令组


219
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:53,800
在这里，我们可以把一系列指令封装成单个指令

220
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:56,100
以节省主程序空间

221
00:04:56,466 --> 00:04:59,733
如果我们想让这个程序组与主程序流程交互

222
00:04:59,733 --> 00:05:03,033
我们可以添加一些指令组节点来执行此操作

223
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:06,966
制作指令组有一个额外的特殊功能

224
00:05:06,966 --> 00:05:11,633
如果我们正在使用稍微不同的指令列表进行一些复杂的设置

225
00:05:11,633 --> 00:05:14,100
我们可以做一个组然后复制它

226
00:05:14,500 --> 00:05:19,500
最后我想展示的有趣东西是伪装升级

227
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:24,033

伪装升级必须和"伪装方块"以及"伪装方块-变换"搭配工作


228
00:05:24,033 --> 00:05:27,400
我们最好将其添加到集线器中以进行适当的布线

229
00:05:27,666 --> 00:05:31,800

有了它，我们可以改变线缆的贴图，让它变得更美观


230
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:33,133
但更重要的是

231
00:05:33,133 --> 00:05:39,833

我们可以改变线缆尺寸，来与被线缆遮挡的方块交互


232
00:05:39,966 --> 00:05:43,000
现在让我们看一些用法示例

233
00:05:43,166 --> 00:05:44,433
在这个净化水厂里

234
00:05:44,433 --> 00:05:52,100
当有红石信号时，我们使用SFM保持输入舱有25L盐酸

235
00:05:52,233 --> 00:05:56,100
为此，我们每秒检查红石条件

236
00:05:56,233 --> 00:06:01,300
如果有红石信号，那么检查仓室内是否已经有液体

237
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:03,200
如果是这样，我们什么都不做

238
00:06:03,266 --> 00:06:07,200
否则，如果有红石并且仓室没有液体

239
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:11,766
我们从主罐中取出25L盐酸并将其移至仓室

240
00:06:11,833 --> 00:06:14,766
这套流程可以通过其他方式实现

241
00:06:14,766 --> 00:06:19,433
但这是一个展示SFM能做什么
以及如何使用它的好例子

242
00:06:20,033 --> 00:06:25,066
在SFM中用的另一个很酷的技巧在下一个净水厂中

243
00:06:25,066 --> 00:06:31,166
我们在库存之间移动一个标志物来确定我们上次执行的操作

244
00:06:31,466 --> 00:06:36,300
下一个例子是用SFM自动化细菌培养缸

245
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:40,266
这里的主要目标是保持输出仓半满

246
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:44,400
但我们也要防止浪费放射性输入材料

247
00:06:44,900 --> 00:06:50,666
为此，我们从输出仓提取除了31桶液体之外的所有东西

248
00:06:50,833 --> 00:06:55,333
然后我们在插入"能够启动配方的放射性棒"之前

249
00:06:55,333 --> 00:06:59,833
检查我们是否有足够的原材料和可用的输出空间

250
00:07:00,066 --> 00:07:02,666
接下来我们有更复杂的任务

251
00:07:02,666 --> 00:07:05,600
例如自动化神秘注魔

252
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:08,400
该程序有两个部分

253
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:12,600
要运行哪部分取决于祭坛中间是否存在物品

254
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:15,500
如果祭坛里没有东西

255
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:19,833
然后我们检查输入箱中是否准备好了订单原料

256
00:07:19,900 --> 00:07:21,900
如果系统没有要执行的任务

257
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:25,100
我们关闭世界加速器以节省能量

258
00:07:25,433 --> 00:07:27,966
但如果我们有东西可以制作

259
00:07:27,966 --> 00:07:30,233
我们把所有物品移动到基座上

260
00:07:30,466 --> 00:07:36,466
为此，我们有一个能够按正确顺序
填充基座的插入指令的指令组

261
00:07:36,666 --> 00:07:41,366
从第一件应该放在祭坛中间的物品开始

262
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:44,433
接下来我们启动所有的世界加速器

263
00:07:44,433 --> 00:07:47,766
并向注魔爪输出红石脉冲以开始注魔

264
00:07:48,066 --> 00:07:49,966
在程序的下一次运行中

265
00:07:49,966 --> 00:07:52,633
我们预计有一件物品在祭坛中间

266
00:07:52,866 --> 00:07:55,300
但要确保注魔已经完成

267
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:59,466
我们还要确定没有其他物品等待处理

268
00:07:59,833 --> 00:08:04,833
如果是这样，我们多等半秒钟以确保一切稳定

269
00:08:04,833 --> 00:08:07,866
然后我们继续取出完成的物品

270
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:11,000
关闭世界加速器

271
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:13,500
如果你想看更多的例子

272
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:16,200
你可以看看我的GTNH第二季

273
00:08:16,433 --> 00:08:17,400
拜拜

274
00:03:53,166 --> 00:03:56,000
（这时候圆石改为任何物品都能达到这个效果）

